\description{
\code{geom_sketch_engrave()} shades a surface the way an etcher or banknote
engraver does: continuous tone is built from the \emph{density} of hand-drawn hatch
lines, with cross-hatching deepening the shadows. It takes a regular grid of
\code{x}, \code{y}, and \code{z} (like \code{\link[ggplot2:geom_raster]{ggplot2::geom_raster()}}); \code{z} is mapped to tone (high
= dark by default). Unlike the fill-pattern packages, the tone is \emph{computed}
from geometry (a \code{\link[=engrave_fill]{engrave_fill()}} ladder), not tiled from a motif.
}
\details{
\code{geom_sketch_shade()} shades each polygon region with a \emph{uniform} density set
by a \code{tone} aesthetic in \verb{[0, 1]}, so a mapped value reads directly as
darkness -- a hand-drawn alternative to a solid fill scale.

The hatch ladder is a stack of layers of increasing density and rotating
angle (\code{levels}, \code{base_gap}, \code{gap_ratio}, \code{base_angle}, \code{cross_after}); each
layer is drawn only where the tone reaches its threshold, so light areas keep
the sparse base layer and shadows accumulate every layer. \code{min_gap_in} is a
pitch floor (inches) that keeps the darkest tones from exploding into a
runaway number of strokes.
}
